text:
Exploit at DeFi Protocol Balancer: Over $100 Million Stolen

The Ethereum-based decentralized trading platform Balancer has fallen victim to a major cyberattack, resulting in the theft of over $100 million in crypto assets. Blockchain analytics firms such as Nansen identified suspicious transfers to a newly created wallet. Balancer confirmed awareness of a potential vulnerability affecting its v2 pools and stated that technical teams are investigating. In response, the Berachain Foundation temporarily halted its network to conduct an emergency hard fork. This incident follows earlier exploits and vulnerabilities, marking another blow to DeFi security and investor confidence.

text:
SLIPPAGE VS PRICE IMPACT 

"I set 3% slippage and still got rekt on a swap. What happened?"

Price impact, slippage, and liquidity are three distinct concepts that are related and sometimes conflated. Here is a short explanation of each.

PRICE IMPACT
Price impact is how much your trade moves the market price. In an onchain exchange like Uniswap prices follow an algorithmic curve. Buying moves the price up this curve and selling moves it down.

How far any one trade moves the price depends on the total liquidity in the pool. If you buy or sell into an illiquid pool even a small swap can move the price a lot. And if the size of your trade is more than the available liquidity in the pool, you will get rekt.

Price impact is not unique to AMMs. The same thing happens if you buy or sell into a thin order book on an offchain exchange. If your trade chews through the order book you will move the mid-market price. How far the price moves depends on how deep the order book liquidity is.

SLIPPAGE
Slippage is the difference between what you expect to receive from a trade and what you actually receive when it executes onchain. Setting "max slippage" protects you if the price moves between time of quote and time of execution. 

How can this happen? In the few seconds between when you see a swap quote and push the button to execute it, other trades may land onchain and move the market price. Again, if there is low liquidity, a few trades landing before yours can move the price a lot.

Setting 3% max slippage means "cancel the trade if I lose more than 3% on what you quoted." But it doesn't protect against the price impact of your own trade.

LIQUIDITY 
Note that both of these concepts are related to liquidity. Liquidity is how much you can trade without moving the price. In an AMM more tokens in the pool means more liquidity. In an offchain exchange more orders in the book means more liquidity. 

TO SUMMARIZE:
Price impact is about how much you move the price with your trade. Slippage is about how much other people move the price before your trade. Both are related to liquidity: less liquidity means small swaps move the price more.

WHAT DOES THIS MEAN FOR MY BAGS?
1. If you are swapping, always look at the quoted amount you receive before you swap. This is the most important number on the screen and is where you will see any potential price impact. If the amount you get back is much lower than the amount you are swapping, your trade has high price impact and you probably should not proceed. 

2. If you are trying to buy or sell a token with a fast moving price or on an L1 with slow blocks, you may need to adjust slippage. 

3. Always pay attention to available liquidity as it impacts 1 and 2. Brand new and obscure tokens are much more likely to have low liquidity. This is also why their prices are often more volatile. You can see liquidity under "Stats" on the token screen.

Founded in 2017, we‚Äôve processed over 78M+ transactions and $140B+ in trading volume from users trading on Matcha, Coinbase Wallet, Robinhood Wallet, Phantom, Rainbow, DefiLlama, MetaMask, Zerion, Zapper, and many more. Our investors include Greylock Partners, Pantera Capital, and Jump Crypto.

When you join 0x, you‚Äôll become part of a veteran team of crypto builders who know the importance of code quality, team cohesion, and a culture of learning.


ROLE

We are looking for a Senior Software Engineer for our Solana and EVM DEX aggregation teams, backend-focused, who have a passion for building DeFi solutions. Our DEX aggregator engineering teams are focused on building the best AMM routers to find the best price at the lowest latency and highest execution quality.

You have a high degree of integrity, learn and adapt quickly, and seek to make a positive impact on the lives of those who use the systems you build. We hire engineers that have solid fundamentals, have strong learning agility, are interested in tackling hard problems and are nice people.


0x Developer Platform Tech Stack

 - Rust ü¶Ä - Most of our backend, critical systems are built with Rust

 - Linux

 - AWS Cloud Services (Kubernetes, Kafka, Postgress, Redis, OpenSearch, etc)

 - Grafana LGTM Observability Stack

 - GitHub

 - We embrace AI as a tool to be better more productive software engineers
   

Responsibilities - Your Mission

 - Be an individual contributor on projects as well as lead technical projects of moderate to high complexity

 - Offer valuable insights as a peer when reviewing designs and performing code reviews

 - Design, build and maintain systems like:
   
   - Blockchain event streaming and indexing services
   
   - Leading edge DEX routing algorithms and models

 - Create high quality, secure, clean code

 - Improve the way we build and deliver software

 - Coach and mentor other engineers and generally up-level the team

 - Empathize with our customers and users
   

Requirements - Who You Are

 - A software engineer with 7+ years of experience solving complex distributed computing problems

 - A generalist who can design and build a system from the ground up which could include:
   
   - Relational or Key Value Data stores
   
   - Distributed Event driven architectures

 - Have lead small to medium sized projects as a tech lead with 2-4 other engineers

 - Are driven by shipping code of high quality with a focus on providing maximum user and business value

Preferred

 - You have a solid understanding of blockchains (Specifically EVM chains and/or Solana)

 - Experience with Web3 libraries (e.g., Alloy, Web3.js, ethers.js http://ethers.js, ether-rs, viem) to build and test blockchain integrations


BENEFITS

show_title: The Tribe Has Spoken (and It‚Äôs Onchain): GM Farcaster ep306 and CastOut launch!
text:
Five days ago, I asked @chaim.eth if there was anything we fans could do to convince him to bring Acid Test back. His answer was, ‚ÄúMay bring it back eventually‚Äù and explained that the revenue from the episodes was not enough to produce the show.

Two days ago, he cast, ‚ÄúHey who‚Äôs up and wants to listen to something weird?‚Äù Then yesterday, he posted the first Acid Test episode after a four-month hiatus. In 24 hours, it earned the equivalent of seven straight weeks on the leaderboard. It is the highest earning episode yet.

I am pointing this number out because I have cast about the leaderboard several times before, encouraging people to think outside of its zero-sum box. But I‚Äôm not sure if the message has fully landed because I still get asked for advice on how to climb the leaderboard.

So here‚Äôs my advice, again:

- ignore the leaderboard presented to you and create your own where the rewards are intrinsic and infinite
- connect with people who genuinely interest you, not targeting individuals to boost your engagement
- follow the call of your weirdness even when you don‚Äôt know who or what you‚Äôll find when you get there
- limit the time between your idea and your experiment so you don‚Äôt overthink your way into not creating
- have fun (what @sayangel has been saying all along)!

Money is an expression of energy. When do you feel most high energy? When you‚Äôre having fun. Start there and see what happens.

cast.text:
Acid Test is a series of high quality interviews focusing on iconic people and moments in Farcaster‚Äôs history. The recent episode is with the creator of the viral Warplets. All previous episodes feature similarly exciting projects in the network. I‚Äôve been a fan since my very first listen.

If you didn‚Äôt know, there is a brief window after every Acid Test episode to mint it. Once the window closes, you can‚Äôt add yourself to the list of collectors. It‚Äôs a fun and simple opportunity to add your name to a little part of network history.

I believe these episodes will age very well. With how fast things change around here, the existing archive is already worth re-visiting. You can still mint your own edition of the most collected episode ever on my most favorite onchain radio show.
